english:
  title: Record of the Pavilion for Pacifying the Barbarians
  author: Choe Bu
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The mountains that rise steeply along the eastern shore of the sea are Bird-Sound Peak; the waters that spread wide at the western foot of those mountains are the Bohai Sea; and between mountain and sea, where streams wind and forests intertwine, where ramparts and fences stretch in all directions, stands Boryeong City.

    At the southeastern corner of the city stands a great eminence, rising like a watchtower to spy the enemy. In the year Xuande renzi, the magistrate Zheng Dai newly built an official residence, leveling the ridge of this hill and constructing a small pavilion upon it—taking advantage of the clean, dry location and affording a vantage for surveying the land. As years accumulated, the residence fell into disrepair and the pavilion into ruin, leaving traveling merchants and passing guests with nowhere to shelter from winter cold or summer heat.

    In the year Hongzhi renzi, Magistrate Park Dison arrived with his seal of office. With order restored and resources abundant, he resolved to rebuild. He gathered officials and common folk to plan the work. Measuring strength and apportioning labor, bearing timber and quarrying stone, he directed carpenter and mason, saw and axe, ruler and plane, all working at his command. The year following saw the completion of the administrative hall; the next year, the magistrate's office; the next, the eastern wing of the guest quarters; and the next, a new pavilion on the former site—its western side opened to draw in the sea breeze, its eastern side furnished with heated floors against the cold wind. Windows gleamed bright, steps rose sharp and clean. The structure stood magnificent, its crimson lacquer catching light like flame. The mountains seemed to rise higher, the sea to spread wider; clouds and mist now seemed to enhance the view itself. Truly, the county had been renewed. New in renzi year, renewed again in renzi year—does not Heaven itself await its appointed time?

    When the pavilion was completed that autumn, I rode southward along the coastal road on official business. Coming from Dragon Valley, I arrived at the county city that morning. The Regional Inspector, Zheng Meishou, had already reached the pavilion ahead of me. Wary of the wind, he had hung curtains and offered me a seat. We spoke and laughed together, shared wine and composed verses. At midday, drawing back the curtains to gaze all around, I beheld delicate clouds adorning the sky, the wind subdued, water and heaven merged in color, cormorants wheeling and settling, herons reflecting white light in the mist, pine-crowned ridges sending forth their green. A thousand forms, ten thousand aspects, suddenly revealing themselves. I gazed in wonder and could not help but exclaim:

    "Is this truly so? What splendor this pavilion commands! I have long drifted across the Bohai and anchored in Ou-Yue; I have crossed the Yangzi and Huai, traveled north. I have tasted many a famous mountain and celebrated water. Yet I had thought our Eastern realm, being small and narrow, could scarcely possess such marvels. Now I see these mountains of Bird-Sound rival the peaks of Kuaiji and Siming as brothers; the waters here compete with Taizhou's sea gate for supremacy; the anchored boats recall the gathering at Jingkou; the tidal bore surpasses the spectacle of Zhejiang's rivers. The lofty peaks rising from the sea exceed even Baozhu Mountain's view of great Yunmeng Lake. What took a thousand leagues to behold in ages past now lies revealed beneath this single pavilion. Breaking through the primordial mist, gazing down upon the four quarters, with clouds and dreams embraced in the heart—can this not contain eight or nine tenths of all wonder?"

    The Inspector, hearing these words, was greatly pleased. He then said to me: "Park the Magistrate—I know him well. He carries within him the wisdom of ancient strategists, yet harbors no ambition for grand office. Many times he has petitioned to return to care for his aging parents, and the throne graciously granted this county as honor for his filial piety. His intentions are commendable. As magistrate, he has expended no public funds, burdened no common people, yet has renewed the pavilion and halls as if heaven itself had wrought it. Is this not the mark of true talent and virtue? Yet the pavilion, being a fortification against wind and raiders, was anciently named 'Hall of Wind Defense'—a purpose far removed from the meaning of the statesman Li Zanyuan's border-defense inscriptions. I have therefore changed the nameplate to 'Pavilion for Pacifying the Barbarians.' Will you not record the origin and meaning of this, and give it lustre?"

    I assented, yet the next day, pressed by urgent duties, I turned my horse toward Ningzhou without taking brush in hand. As months passed, the Inspector sent word urging me again. Unable to decline, I wrote this reply:

    The rise and fall of a single pavilion may seem a small matter, yet through it we may discern the waxing and waning of the nation's fortune. In the declining days of Goryeo, when the frontier lands fell prey to sea pirates and war brought desolation, leaving no smoke of hearth or home—how could one then pacify the distant peoples? Though one might wish to raise pavilions and towers to ease such anguish, it could not be done.

    But our nation, by positioning defenses wisely and garrisoning key strongholds, has secured these vital passes. Consider this city: twenty li to the west lies the Naval Command; some hundred li to the northwest, the Military Administration Office; to the south it borders Nampo; and further south stand the fortresses of Maryang and Biin, all arrayed in interlocking formation. The watchtower stands vigilant, the soldiers attend to both arms and agriculture. A hundred years have passed in such peace. Now this pavilion rises prominent among them, manifesting today's reign of great peace. Is it not fitting then that it bear the name 'Pacifying the Barbarians'?

    Yet pacifying brigands, barbarians, and common folk alike—this cannot be achieved by fortification alone, nor by abundance of grain and strength of army. The spreading of civil virtue and the arts of conciliation are matters already resolved in the halls of government. Those who receive these directives and govern in the provinces—if they exhaust themselves in the true methods of pacification, what they gain even from a single pavilion shall suffice.

    When ascending this pavilion, do not be seduced by mere scenery, do not indulge excessively in wine and verse. Rather, gazing upon the fields, contemplate their cultivation; gazing upon the waters and walls, consider their preservation; gazing upon the schools, consider their flourishing. See the merchants and think of their welfare; see the old and young and think of their care. Even the birds and fish, the grasses and trees—seek their flourishing. Where there is sight, there must be thought; where there is thought, there must be duty fulfilled. Then will virtue spread ever wider, the sea waves grow ever calmer, and even the distant barbarians of the nine regions draw ever closer in submission. This pavilion's construction shall endure with mountain and sea unto their end. This is the charge upon the Inspector and Magistrate Park. Redouble your efforts, and may those who come after as magistrate and inspector heed this charge as well.
  footnotes:
    - Bird-Sound Peak (鳥聲) refers to a mountain near present-day Boryeong, Korea. The poetic naming follows the Chinese literary tradition of personifying natural landmarks.
    - The Xuande era (宣德, 1426-1435) and Hongzhi era (弘治, 1488-1505) mark two periods of renovation, both occurring in renzi years—a coincidence the author notes as significant.
    - Li Zanyuan (李贊皇) was a famous Tang dynasty general known for his strategic wisdom and border defense policies, here invoked as a model of administrative excellence.
    - The 'nine regions' (九州) traditionally refers to all civilized lands under proper governance, with 'barbarians' representing those beyond the sphere of civil influence—not necessarily pejorative in classical usage, but indicating those requiring gentle influence through virtue.
